While I still think Angelina Jolie is perfect for the part, you guys just turned everything around. Heck, it wouldn‚Äôt surprise me if Aurora was the real bad guy in this movie. It‚Äôd match the characterizations of the last movie. The one that turned the evil fairy into a good guy, the lovably idiotic kings into unlikable idiotic @$$holes, and the three good fairies into the worst characters ever. text: (Christ Witnesses to Nicodemus on being born again and what it means):    The same came to Jesus by night,   and said unto him,    Rabbi,    we know that thou   art a teacher come from God:  for no man can do these miracles   that thou doest,   except God be with him.    Jesus answered   and said unto him,    Verily, verily,   I say unto thee,    Except a man   be born again,    he cannot see   the kingdom of God.    (John 3:2-3).    ***The fact that Nicodemus came to Jesus by night may reveal the timidity of his faith. (12:42). However, his faith was developing. (John 7:50-51)<---Nicodemus saith unto them, (he that came to Jesus by night, being one of them,) Doth our law judge any man, before it hear him, and know what he doeth?) (John 19:39)<---And there came also Nicodemus, which at the first came to Jesus by night, and brought a mixture of myrrh and aloes, about an hundred pound weight).    ***(Born again): The Greek word translated again can mean either "from above" or "anew." The new birth, or regeneration,    (Titus 3:5)<---Not by works of righteousness which we have done, but according to his mercy he saved us, by the washing of regeneration, and renewing of the (Holy Ghost), is the act by which God imparts spiritual life to one who trusts Christ. Without this spiritual birth, a person cannot perceive spiritual things, (1 Corinthians 2:10)<---But God hath revealed them unto us by his Spirit: for the Spirit searcheth all things, yea, the deep things of God). (1 Corinthians 2:13-16)<---Which things also we speak, not in the words which man's wisdom teacheth, but which the Holy Ghost teacheth; comparing spiritual things with spiritual. But the natural man receiveth not the things of the Spirit of God: for they are foolishness unto him: neither can he know them, because they are spiritually discerned. But he that is spiritual judgeth all things, yet he himself is judged of no man. For who hath known the mind of the Lord, that he may instruct him? But we have the mind of Christ), nor can he or she enter the kingdom of God. (Verse 5).    (BORN AGAIN):    (Gk. gennao anothen) (3:3,7) Strong's #1080; 509: The Greek word anothen translated here as again could also be rendered "from above."  The birth that Jesus spoke of was either a new birth or a heavenly birth---or both. It seems that Jesus was speaking of a heavenly birth because he later used the analogy of the wind, coming from some unknown, heavenly source, to depict the spiritual birth. But Nicodemus clearly understood Jesus to be speaking of a second birth--being born again. Jesus explains this new or heavenly birth in 3:6-8, contrasting being born of the flesh with being born of the spirit.

text: Queen Aurora (then Princess Aurora) struggles to uphold the kingdom left by her father and is already receiving threats from neighboring kingdoms. Queen Ingris (Michelle Pfeiffer) is no exception and plans to invade Aurora's kingdom. The young queen enlists the help of an old friend, Maleficent (Angelina Jolie) and they set off to start a treaty between the two kingdoms. Things start to go downhill when Queen Ingris starts to mock and belittle the young Queen Aurora and her advisors. Maleficent isn't keen on receiving mockery and insults for she IS the Mistress of Evil. She lashes out on the Queen and her subjects and they take this as an act of war. Now, the young Queen Aurora has no choice but to rally her men and do all that she can to save her already crumbling kingdom.

The point of the first movie (Maleficent) is that there is a lot more to the story then a petty fairy who tries to kill a little girl for the sole reason of not being invited to her party. So no Disney didn‚Äôt just make her good and then changed their mind to make her evil again. They gave her a backstory, and made her more human and relatable. We now can empathize what she went through, and see her eventual ‚Äúevil deeds‚Äù in a new light. She was always to become ‚Äúevil‚Äù with a sequel or not, thats the story we know. (Simple terms: Maleficent = prequel, and Maleficent 2 I consider a remake of sleeping beauty)  But the debate of wether the second movie should have been made then it‚Äôs totally valid. Anyways that‚Äôs just my two cents.

Question: "What are the essentials of the gospel message?"   Answer:  The word gospel means ‚Äúgood news,‚Äù which is the message of forgiveness for sin through the atoning work of Jesus Christ. It is essentially God‚Äôs rescue plan of redemption for those who will trust in His divine Son Jesus Christ in order to be reconciled to a just and holy God. The essential content of this saving message is clearly laid out for us in the Bible.   In the apostle Paul‚Äôs first letter to the Corinthians, he lays out the content of the gospel message, ‚ÄúNow, brothers and sisters, I want to remind you of the gospel I preached to you, which you received and on which you have taken your stand. By this gospel you are saved, if you hold firmly to the word I preached to you. Otherwise, you have believed in vain. For what I received I passed on to you as of first importance: that Christ died for our sins according to the Scriptures, that he was buried, that he was raised on the third day according to the Scriptures‚Äù (1 Corinthians 15:1‚Äì4).   In this passage, we see three essential elements of the gospel message. First, the phrase ‚Äúdied for our sins‚Äù is very important. As Romans 3:23 tells us, ‚ÄúFor all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God.‚Äù The reality of sin needs to be acknowledged by all who approach the throne of God for salvation. A sinner must acknowledge the hopelessness of his guilt before God in order for forgiveness to take place, and he must understand that the ‚Äúwages of sin is death‚Äù (Romans 6:23). Without this foundational truth, no gospel presentation is complete.   Second, the person and work of Christ are indispensable components of the gospel. Jesus is both God (Colossians 2:9) and man (John 1:14). Jesus lived the sinless life that we could never live (1 Peter 2:22), and, because of that, He is the only one who could die a substitutionary death for the sinner. Sin against an infinite God requires an infinite sacrifice. Therefore, either man, who is finite, must pay the penalty for an infinite length of time in hell, or the infinite Christ must pay for it once. Jesus went to the cross to pay the debt we owe to God for our sin, and those who are covered by His sacrifice will inherit the kingdom of God as sons of the king (John 1:12).   Third, the resurrection of Christ is an essential element of the gospel. The resurrection is the proof of the power of God. Only He who created life can resurrect it after death, only He can reverse the hideousness that is death itself, and only He can remove the sting that is death and the victory that is the grave‚Äôs (1 Corinthians 15:54‚Äì55). Further, unlike all other religions, Christianity alone possesses a Founder who transcends death and who promises that His followers will do the same. All other religions were founded by men and prophets whose end was the grave.   Finally, Christ offers His salvation as a free gift (Romans 5:15; 6:23), that can only be received by faith, apart from any works or merit on our part (Ephesians 2:8‚Äì9). As the apostle Paul tells us, the gospel is ‚Äúthe power of God that brings salvation to everyone who believes: first to the Jew, then to the Gentile‚Äù (Romans 1:16). The same inspired author tells us, ‚ÄúIf you declare with your mouth, ‚ÄòJesus is Lord,‚Äô and believe in your heart that God raised him from the dead, you will be saved‚Äù (Romans 10:9).   These, then, are the essential elements of the gospel: the sin of all men, the death of Christ on the cross to pay for those sins, the resurrection of Christ to provide life everlasting for those who follow Him, and the offer of the free gift of salvation to all.   What Does Faith Mean?   Faith is one of those words that is commonly used but not always understood. Some of that confusion comes from the many different ways the word faith is used in everyday conversation; a quick look at Dictionary.com shows seven different uses! One common way that people use the word faith is to refer to belief in something despite lacking any evidence for it. But is that what the Bible means by faith? The answer is a resounding no! So, when the Bible uses the word faith, what does it mean?  The closest that the Bible comes to offering an exact definition is Hebrews 11:1: ‚ÄúNow faith is the assurance of things hoped for, the conviction of things not seen.‚Äù From this particular passage we see that the central feature of faith‚Äîconfidence or trust. In the Bible, the object of faith is God and his promises. A clear example of this is Abram's encounter with God in Genesis 15. In response to God's promise of countless descendants, Abram ‚Äúbelieved the LORD, and he counted it to him as righteousness‚Äù (Gen 15:6). Commenting on this, the Apostle Paul writes, ‚ÄúNo unbelief made him waver concerning the promise of God, but he grew strong in his faith as he gave glory to God, fully convinced that God was able to do what he had promised‚Äù (Rom 4:20‚Äì21). Thus, faith means putting your trust in God and having confidence that he will fulfill his promises.  Faith is more than intellectual agreement. To use an old illustration, imagine you are at Niagara Falls watching a tightrope walker push a wheelbarrow across the rope high above the falls. After watching him go back and forth several times, he asks for a volunteer to sit in the wheelbarrow as he pushes it across the falls. At an intellectual level, you may believe that he could successfully push you across the rope over the falls, but you are not exercising biblical faith until you get in the wheelbarrow and entrust yourself to the tightrope walker.  Genuine biblical faith expresses itself in everyday life. James writes that ‚Äúfaith by itself, apart from works, is dead‚Äù (James 2:17). Faith works through love to produce tangible evidence of its existence in a person's life (Gal 5:6). Put another way, the obedience that pleases God comes from faith (Rom 1:5, 16:26), rather than a mere sense of duty or obligation. There is all the difference in the world between the husband who buys his wife flowers out of delight and one who buys them simply out of duty.  Faith is so important because it is the means by which we have a relationship with God: ‚ÄúFor by grace you have been saved through faith‚Äù (Eph 2:8). Faith is how we receive the benefits of what Jesus has done for us. He lived a life of perfect obedience to God, died to pay the penalty for our sinful rebellion against God, and rose from the dead to defeat sin, death, and the devil. By putting our faith in him, we receive forgiveness for our sins and the gift of eternal life.  So, faith means relying completely on who Jesus is and what he has done to be made right with God.

text: So... I guess Disney heard all my complaints about the first movie being too wishy-washy, saying Maleficent was both hero and villain when she was 157% portrayed as the hero.  You want evil Maleficent? Oh, we‚Äôll give you evil Maleficent!  Sigh... fine.  I appreciate that Disney has amped up the production quality of its sequels, as opposed to the laughable direct-to-video sequel period of the 90‚Äôs (thanks, Eisner), buuuuuut... a sequel is still a sequel. A safe investment. A regurgitation of material that, in this case, wasn‚Äôt that good to begin with.  And to be clear, this is a sequel to a live-action remake of an animated adaptation of an original fairy tale. Yeesh.  I mean... not to sound too entitled, but could we at least get a couple more live-action remakes of animated classics before we start getting sequels to remakes? text: I hope this time they have one important male character who isn't evil, incompetent, or useless. In _Sleeping Beauty_ (1959), Prince Philip was charming, brave, and competent. I was disappointed that he was reduced to a prop with no character and no purpose but to be pretty. Maleficent wouldn't even let let let him ride his own horse, she knocked him out and had him carried as a piece of luggage. How ignoble. The movie had much going for it but it was grating how the feminist revisionism sought to make amends for superficial female characters in earlier eras (though not in _Sleeping Beauty)_ by going to an extreme in the other direction and dehumanizing the men. The men shown to be unnecessary to the women, who were willing to live together happily in the forest without men forever. I was almost expecting a lesbian wedding between Maleficent and Princess Aurora at the end of the first film. We may just be a remake or two away from seeing that.  I really liked the rationale for Maleficent's curse and her backstory, so I hope this sequel builds on it's strengths with complex and surprising.character development. Turning Maleficent into a convincing benign fairy godmother was a clever and delicious twist.
